<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1396,2035]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1432,1459]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fifth instar immature</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[476,575,1433,1460]" captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 168</figureCitation>
). Body elongate, 1.3–1.9 times as long as wide, weakly sclerotised. Antenna 8 or 9-segmented, sometimes division between segments 8 and 9 incomplete; sparsely beset with setae which are not longer than diameter of flagellum; bearing a single subapical rhinarium on each of segments 3, 5, 7 and 8. Dorsal body surface sparsely covered in moderately long setae. Forewing pad about half to three quarters of antennal length, oval, lacking humeral lobes; margin with short and long normal and weakly or distinctly capitate setae; dorsum with normal (
<figureCitation box="[359,455,1613,1640]" captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 169</figureCitation>
) and/or indistinctly capitate setae (
<figureCitation box="[851,950,1613,1639]" captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 170</figureCitation>
). Margin of hindwing pad with moderately long, imperceptibly or distinctly capitate setae; lacking sectasetae. Legs long, with a few long, very weakly capitate setae on tibiae and many short and long setae; tarsal arolium long, twice as long as claws, subtrapezoidal, with unguitractor and pedicel (
<figureCitation box="[447,547,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 171</figureCitation>
). Abdomen suboval, broadly rounded terminally; caudal plate weakly sclerotised; abdominal margin with 4+4 truncate sectasetae which are grouped together, each on a small bump (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs 168, 172–174</figureCitation>
), positioned on either side of circumanal rings close to the outer ring. Anus in terminal position; outer circumanal ring relatively large, indented medially, more or less expanding laterally, mostly onto abdominal dorsum (
<figureCitation box="[159,318,1865,1891]" captionStart="FIGURES 168–174" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1441,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1420]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[151,1436,625,1421]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 168–174. Mitrapsylla spp., immatures; 168, habitus, in dorsal view; ss = sectasetae; 169, 170, forewing pad; 171, tarsal arolium; 172–174, right half of caudal plate; d = dorsal portion of outer circumanal ring, ss = sectasetae.—168, M. adusta sp. nov.; 169, 172, M. copaiferae sp. nov.; 170, 171, M. fumipennis sp. nov.; 173, M. gloriae sp. nov.; 174, M. repens sp. nov.—Scales 168 = 0.5 mm; 169, 170 = 0.1 mm; 171 = 0.03 mm; 172–174 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669679/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs 172–174</figureCitation>
), consisting, at least partially, of several rows of irregular, oval wax pores which are about twice as long as wide; extra pore fields absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,1396,2035]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,253,1937,1963]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Egg.</emphasis>
About 
<quantity box="[340,429,1937,1963]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
long; oblong oval, about twice as long as wide; irregularly narrowing at apex which is subacute (
<figureCitation box="[265,349,1973,2000]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1290,1315]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,445,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,445,1271]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Eggs of psyllids associated with Detarieae; 22, Apsyllopsis mexicana; 23, Colophorina guarani sp. nov.; 24, Platycorypha amazonica sp. nov.; 25, Jataiba uncigera sp. nov.; 26, Mitrapsylla sp.—Scales 0.2 mm; 24–26 = scale 26." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3669655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3669655/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Judging from the few eggs we have seen in the cleared abdomina of females, it appears that the eggs are soft-shelled and only weakly sclerotised.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,152,467]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,152,179]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[342,473,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[342,473,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mitrapsylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains 15 valid described species, for five of which there are host records. Four species are reported from faboid legumes and one from a caesalpinoid legume. Here we describe nine new species from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,219,225,251]" name="Brazil" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Brazil</collectingCountry>
which are associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[525,639,225,251]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Copaifera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[525,639,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Copaifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(confirmed or likely). 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown &amp; Hodkinson" authorityName="Brown &amp; Hodkinson" box="[897,1412,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuticonis">
<emphasis box="[897,1166,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mitrapsylla minuticonis</emphasis>
Brown &amp; Hodkinson
</taxonomicName>
, a species described from 
<collectingCountry box="[415,507,261,287]" name="Panama" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Panama</collectingCountry>
, is morphologically similar and probably closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz, 2020" authorityName="Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz" authorityYear="2020" box="[1175,1333,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copaiferae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1175,1333,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">M. copaiferae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1339,1429,261,287]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1339,1429,261,287]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, suggesting that it develops also on 
<taxonomicName box="[539,653,297,323]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Copaifera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[539,653,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Copaifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The immatures of only five species are known. Adults and immatures of 
<taxonomicName box="[182,313,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[182,313,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mitrapsylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be identified with keys provided below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,152,467]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
The description of immature ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1944" box="[540,775,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserata">
<emphasis box="[540,775,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mitrapsylla deserata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Caldwell’ and hence the concept of 
<taxonomicName box="[1193,1324,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Mitrapsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1193,1324,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Mitrapsylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="White, I. M. &amp; Hodkinson, I. D." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="153 - 301" refId="ref72112" refString="White, I. M. &amp; Hodkinson, I. D. (1985) Nymphal taxonomy and systematics of Psylloidea (Homoptera). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology Series, 50, 153 - 301." type="journal article" year="1985">White and Hodkinson (1985)</bibRefCitation>
probably concern 
<taxonomicName authority="Caldwell and Martorell" authorityName="Caldwell and Martorell" authorityYear="1941" box="[610,1148,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Heteropsylla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huasachae">
<emphasis box="[610,881,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Heteropsylla huasachae</emphasis>
Caldwell and Martorell
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Burckhardt, D. &amp; Brown, R. G." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="290 - 301" refId="ref69471" refString="Burckhardt, D. &amp; Brown, R. G. (1992) Larvae of Panamanian jumping plant-lice (Homoptera: Psylloidea). In: Aiello, D. A. (Ed.), Insects of Panama and Mesoamerica: selected studies. Oxford, pp. 290 - 301." type="book chapter" year="1992">Burckhardt &amp; Brown 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
